{"cursor":"2880","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n'Antoine Christophe Merlin' (13 September 1762, Thionville, Moselle â 14\nSeptember 1833) was a member of several legislative bodies during the era of the\nFrench Revolution. He is usually called \"Merlin de Thionville\" (\"Merlin of\nThionville\") to distinguish him from Philippe-Antoine Merlin de Douai.\n\nHe was born at Thionville, the son of a procureur in the\n[[Bailiwick|bailliage]] of Thionville. After studying theology, he began a\ncareer in law, and in 1788 was an avocat at the [[parlement]] of Metz. In 1790\nhe was elected municipal officer of Thionville, and was sent by the department\nof Moselle to the Legislative Assembly. On 23 October 1791 he moved and carried\nthe institution of a committee of surveillance, of which he became a member. It\nwas he who proposed the law sequestrating the property of the Ã©migrÃ©s, and he\ntook an important part in the Ã©meute of 20 June 1792 and in the revolution of\n10 August of the same year.\n\nHe was elected deputy to the National Convention, and pressed for the execution\nof Louis XVI, but a mission to the army prevented his attending the trial. He\ndisplayed great bravery in the defence of Mainz. He took part in the\nThermidorian Reaction which followed the fall of Robespierre, sat in the Council\nof Five Hundred under the Directory, and at the [[coup d'Ã©tat]] of the 18th\nFructidor (4 September 1797) demanded the deportation of certain republican\nmembers. In 1798 he ceased to be a member of the Council of Five Hundred, and\nwas appointed director-general of posts, being sent subsequently to organize the\narmy of Italy. He retired into private life at the proclamation of the\nConsulate, and lived in retirement under the Consulate and the Empire.\n","linknr":131,"url":"Antoine_Merlin_de_Thionville","recorded":1375082310,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Antoine_Christophe_Merlin&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Antoine_Christophe_Merlin&action=e